                    <Grid x:Name="grid2" Background="#41AC5353" VerticalAlignment="Top" Height="1123">
                        <Button Content="Thank you, NEXT!!!" VerticalAlignment="Bottom" Height="68" FontSize="18" Background="#FFB65757" BorderBrush="{x:Null}" Click="Open_Vocabulary"/>
                        <Label x:Name="label5" Content="The Verb" VerticalAlignment="Top" Height="75" Width="572" FontSize="36" HorizontalContentAlignment="Center" VerticalContentAlignment="Center" HorizontalAlignment="Center" IsEnabled="False" Foreground="Black" Margin="0,0,-17,0"/>
                        <TextBlock x:Name="txt1" TextWrapping="Wrap" Margin="0,75,0,68" Padding="20,0" FontSize="16"><Run Text="We commonly use the present simple to refer to the past when we want to make events sound as if they are happening now. For example, news headlines are commonly written in the present simple:"/><LineBreak/><Run TextDecorations="Underline"/><LineBreak/><Run Text="Rebels attack government buildings." TextDecorations="Underline"/><LineBreak/><Run TextDecorations="Underline"/><LineBreak/><Run Text="German Finance minister resigns." TextDecorations="Underline"/><LineBreak/><Run TextDecorations="Underline"/><LineBreak/><Run Text="In formal writing the present simple is also used to refer to important events in the past:"/><LineBreak/><Run TextDecorations="Underline"/><LineBreak/><Run Text="In spring 1984 the government is defeated and an election takes place. By the end of the year the strikes end." TextDecorations="Underline"/><LineBreak/><Run TextDecorations="Underline"/><LineBreak/><Run Text="We also use the present simple when we tell stories or jokes. It makes them sound more immediate:"/><LineBreak/><Run TextDecorations="Underline"/><LineBreak/><Run Text="It's seven o'clock in the evening and an old woman walks slowly out of her garden and towards the bus stop. The soldier watches her and after a few minutes follows her." TextDecorations="Underline"/><LineBreak/><Run TextDecorations="Underline"/><LineBreak/><Run Text="A man walks into a restaurant with a monkey on his shoulder. The monkey says, 'I'd like soup please.'" TextDecorations="Underline"/><LineBreak/><Run TextDecorations="Underline"/><LineBreak/><Run Text="We also use the present simple when we report what people say as part of a story:"/><LineBreak/><Run TextDecorations="Underline"/><LineBreak/><Run Text="It was only eleven o'clock and my mum says, 'You're late again.' And I say, 'No, I'm not.' Then my dad starts to shout." TextDecorations="Underline"/><LineBreak/><Run TextDecorations="Underline"/><LineBreak/><Run Text="We use the present simple for future reference in subordinate clauses after words like when, before, as soon as, if and whether:"/><LineBreak/><Run TextDecorations="Underline"/><LineBreak/><Run Text="I'll call you when I get there." TextDecorations="Underline"/><LineBreak/><Run TextDecorations="Underline"/><LineBreak/><Run FontWeight="Bold" Text="Not: I'll call you when I'll get there." TextDecorations="Underline"/><LineBreak/><Run TextDecorations="Underline"/><LineBreak/><Run Text="Don't forget to ring before you go." TextDecorations="Underline"/><LineBreak/><Run TextDecorations="Underline"/><LineBreak/><Run FontWeight="Bold" Text="Not: Don't forget to ring before you'll go." TextDecorations="Underline"/><LineBreak/><Run TextDecorations="Underline"/><LineBreak/><Run Text="They hope to move in to the new house as soon as they get back from Australia next month." TextDecorations="Underline"/><LineBreak/><Run TextDecorations="Underline"/><LineBreak/><Run FontWeight="Bold" Text="Not: … as soon as they'll get back from Australia next month." TextDecorations="Underline"/><LineBreak/><LineBreak/><Run TextDecorations="Underline"/></TextBlock>
