                        <TextBlock x:Name="textBlock88" TextWrapping="Wrap" VerticalAlignment="Top" Margin="0,75,0,0" Height="800" Padding="20,0"><Run FontWeight="Bold" FontSize="16" Text="Adverbs: comparative and superlative forms"/><LineBreak/><Run FontSize="16" Text="Adverbs do not normally change in form, but a few have comparative and superlative forms. These are usually short adverbs and so they normally have comparative and superlative forms with -er and -est."/><LineBreak/><Run FontSize="16" Text="Some of the most common comparative and superlative adverbs are:"/><LineBreak/><Run FontStyle="Italic" FontSize="16" Text="soon sooner soonest // fast faster fastest"/><LineBreak/><Run FontStyle="Italic" FontSize="16" Text="hard harder hardest // near nearer nearest"/><LineBreak/><Run FontStyle="Italic" FontSize="16" Text="early earlier earliest // light lighter lightest etc."/><LineBreak/><Run FontStyle="Italic" FontSize="16"/><LineBreak/><Run FontWeight="Bold" FontSize="16" Text="Adverbs with more and most"/><LineBreak/><Run FontSize="16" Text="Adverbs with two or more syllables form the comparative and superlative with more and most:"/><LineBreak/><Run FontSize="16" Text="We need to treat the environment more carefully." TextDecorations="Underline"/><LineBreak/><Run FontSize="16" Text="It was the most beautifully designed chair." TextDecorations="Underline"/><LineBreak/><Run FontStyle="Italic" FontSize="16" Text=" "/><LineBreak/><Run FontWeight="Bold" FontSize="16" Text="Comparative adverbs: using than"/><LineBreak/><Run FontSize="16" Text="When we mention the second person or thing in the comparison, we use than. We do not use that or as. If the second person mentioned takes the form of a personal pronoun, we normally use the object form of the pronoun (me, you, him, her, us, them):"/><LineBreak/><Run FontSize="16" Text="I can't keep up with him – he runs much faster than me." TextDecorations="Underline"/><LineBreak/><Run FontWeight="Bold" FontSize="16" Text="Not" TextDecorations="Underline"/><Run FontSize="16" Text=": faster that me or faster as me" TextDecorations="Underline"/><LineBreak/><Run FontStyle="Italic" FontSize="16"/><LineBreak/><Run FontSize="16" Text="In more formal situations, instead of than + object pronoun, we can use than + subject pronoun + be, do or a modal verb:"/><LineBreak/><Run FontSize="16" Text="My wife drives more carefully than I do." TextDecorations="Underline"/><LineBreak/><Run FontSize="16" Text="She can read music much more quickly than I can." TextDecorations="Underline"/><LineBreak/><Run FontSize="16" Text=" "/><LineBreak/><Run FontWeight="Bold" FontSize="16" Text="Well and badly"/><LineBreak/><Run FontSize="16" Text="The adverb well has the same comparative and superlative forms as the adjective good (better, best). The adverb badly has the comparative and superlative forms worse, worst:"/><LineBreak/><Run FontSize="16" Text="[talking about playing tennis]"/><LineBreak/><Run FontSize="16" Text="I played better yesterday but I need to improve my serve." TextDecorations="Underline"/><LineBreak/><Run FontSize="16" Text="A lot of people behaved badly at the party, but she behaved worst of all." TextDecorations="Underline"/><LineBreak/><Run/></TextBlock>
                    </Grid>
