                    <Grid x:Name="grid111" Background="#41AC5353" VerticalAlignment="Top" Height="1022">
                        <Button Content="Thank you, NEXT!!!" VerticalAlignment="Bottom" Height="68" FontSize="18" Background="#FFB65757" BorderBrush="{x:Null}" Click="Open_Vocabulary"/>
                        <Label x:Name="label111" Content="So &amp; Such" HorizontalAlignment="Center" VerticalAlignment="Top" Height="75" Width="555" FontSize="36" HorizontalContentAlignment="Center" VerticalContentAlignment="Center"/>
                        <TextBlock x:Name="textBlock1111" TextWrapping="Wrap" VerticalAlignment="Top" Margin="0,75,0,0" Height="879" FontSize="16" Padding="20,0"><Run Text="We can use so after some verbs instead of repeating an object clause, especially in short answers. The verbs we do this with most are: appear, assume, be afraid (meaning 'regret'), believe, expect, guess, hope, imagine, presume, reckon, seem, suppose, think:"/><LineBreak/><Run/><LineBreak/><Run Text="Chris thinks the tickets are too expensive, and Madeline thinks so too."/><LineBreak/><Run/><LineBreak/><Run Text="(… and Madeline thinks the tickets are expensive.)"/><LineBreak/><Run/><LineBreak/><Run Text="A:"/><LineBreak/><Run Text="Are you working on Saturday?"/><LineBreak/><Run/><LineBreak/><Run Text="B:"/><LineBreak/><Run Text="I'm afraid so. I wish I wasn't! (I'm afraid I'm working.)"/><LineBreak/><Run/><LineBreak/><Run Text="A:"/><LineBreak/><Run Text="D'you think the weather's going to be fine tomorrow?"/><LineBreak/><Run/><LineBreak/><Run Text="B:"/><LineBreak/><Run Text="I hope so. I want to do some work in the garden. (I hope the weather's "/><LineBreak/><Run Text="going to be fine.)"/><LineBreak/><Run/><LineBreak/><Run Text="We can use not after be afraid, guess, hope and suppose instead of using a negative object clause:"/><LineBreak/><Run/><LineBreak/><Run Text="A:"/><LineBreak/><Run Text="Can we speak to Mr Brindley, please?"/><LineBreak/><Run/><LineBreak/><Run Text="B:"/><LineBreak/><Run Text="I'm afraid not. He's busy. (I'm afraid you cannot speak to Mr Brindley.)"/><LineBreak/><Run/><LineBreak/><Run Text="A:"/><LineBreak/><Run Text="It looks as if Louis won't be coming with us after all."/><LineBreak/><Run/><LineBreak/><Run Text="B:"/><LineBreak/><Run Text="I guess not. It's a pity."/><LineBreak/><Run/><LineBreak/><Run Text="She thinks she might lose her job in the New Year, but she hopes not."/><LineBreak/><Run/><LineBreak/><Run Text="With believe, expect and think, we normally use auxiliary do + not + main verb + so:"/><LineBreak/><Run/><LineBreak/><Run Text="A:"/><LineBreak/><Run Text="Did Frances come here this morning?"/><LineBreak/><Run/><LineBreak/><Run Text="B:"/><LineBreak/><Run Text="I don't believe so. Ask Hannah."/><LineBreak/><Run/><LineBreak/><Run Text="They asked Wilma if she thought her mother would refuse the invitation. She said she didn't think so."/><LineBreak/><Run/><LineBreak/><Run Text="We can find believe not, expect not and think not in classic literature and in very formal situations, but it is not common in everyday modern English:"/><LineBreak/><Run/><LineBreak/><Run Text="[from the novel Dombey and Son (1848) by Charles Dickens]"/><LineBreak/><Run/><LineBreak/><Run Text="'He is in England, I hope, aunt?' said the child."/><LineBreak/><Run/><LineBreak/><Run Text="'I believe so. Yes; I know he is, indeed.'"/><LineBreak/><Run/><LineBreak/><Run Text="'Has he ever been here?'"/><LineBreak/><Run/><LineBreak/><Run Text="'I believe not. No.'"/><LineBreak/><Run/><LineBreak/><Run Text="Are we prepared to change our entire lives for the sake of one person? I think not."/><LineBreak/><Run/><LineBreak/><Run Text=" "/><LineBreak/><Run Text="Typical errors"/><LineBreak/><Run Text="We don't use so + object clause together:"/><LineBreak/><Run/><LineBreak/><Run Text="A:"/><LineBreak/><Run Text="Is George coming today?"/><LineBreak/><Run/><LineBreak/><Run Text="B:"/><LineBreak/><Run Text="I don't think so."/><LineBreak/><Run/><LineBreak/><Run Text="Not: I don't think so he's coming today."/><LineBreak/><Run/><LineBreak/><Run Text="We don't say I think or I don't think without so in short answers:"/><LineBreak/><Run/><LineBreak/><Run Text="A:"/><LineBreak/><Run Text="Is next Monday a public holiday?"/><LineBreak/><Run/><LineBreak/><Run Text="B:"/><LineBreak/><Run Text="Yes, I think so."/><LineBreak/><Run/><LineBreak/><Run Text="Not: Yes, I think."/></TextBlock>
